ershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Chipping Campden, Cotswold, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harding","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Harding</i> (Old English <i>Hearding</i>, literally ‘the hard one’ a derivative of Old English <i>heard</i> ‘hard, harsh, strong, firm, brave’). The surname was first taken to Ireland in the 15th century, and more families of the name settled there 200 years later in Tipperary and surrounding counties.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’, or a habitational name from a farm named Harding, of the same etymology.","History: Warren Gamaliel Harding (1865–1923), the 29th president of the US, was born on a farm in OH, of English and Scottish stock on his father's side. Early American bearers of this very common name include Joseph Harding who died at Plymouth in 1633. His great-great grandson Seth was a naval officer during the American Revolution."],"variants":[{"name":"Hardin","meanings":["English: variant of   Harding  .","Altered form of French   Hardouin  .","French: from a pet form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names composed of the element <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Arduino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Francisco, Jose, Luis, Marina, Alberto, Alfonso, Alturo, Angel, Arturo, Azucena, Basilio, Carlos.  Italian Antonio, Gabino.","Italian and Hispanic: from the personal name <i>Arduino</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, akin to   Harding   2."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":3,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Harding was born about 1287, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Ralph de Harding, was 24 and his mother, Christina Gilbert, was 16. He married Mary Lamb de Prez in 1300, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1305, in Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 19, and was buried in Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom.